export const FISH_KNOWLEDGE: string = "# Aquaculture Knowledge Base — West African Fish Farming\n\n## Species Overview\n\n### Catfish (Clarias gariepinus — African Mud Catfish)\n- Most common commercial species in Nigeria, Cameroon, Ghana\n- Hardy, air-breathing — tolerates low DO better than tilapia\n- Market weight: 600g–1.5kg (typically 800g–1kg for table fish)\n- Grow-out period: 4–6 months from fingerling to harvest\n- Stocking density: 50–150 fish/m³ in tanks; 1–3 fish/m² in earthen ponds\n- FCR: 1.2–1.8 (good management); target ≤1.5\n- Fingerling size at stocking: 5–10g (post-juvenile, 6–8 weeks old)\n- Weekly ABW targets:\n  - Week 4: ~20g\n  - Week 8: ~80g\n  - Week 12: ~200g\n  - Week 16: ~400g\n  - Week 20: ~700g\n  - Week 24: ~900g–1.2kg (harvest window)\n\n### Tilapia (Oreochromis niloticus — Nile Tilapia)\n- Second most farmed species in the region\n- Cannot breathe air — more sensitive to low DO than catfish\n- Market weight: 400g–800g\n- Grow-out period: 5–7 months\n- Stocking density: 1–3 fish/m² earthen pond; 20–50/m³ tanks\n- FCR: 1.5–2.0\n- Prone to overpopulation if mixed sexes — use mono-sex (male) fingerlings\n- Weekly ABW targets roughly 60–70% of catfish at same age\n\n### Clarias (Clarias species / Heteroclarias hybrid)\n- Hybrid between C. gariepinus and Heterobranchus bidorsalis\n- Fastest grower of the three; often reaches 1kg in 4 months\n- Higher feed cost but better FCR (1.0–1.4)\n\n## Water Quality Parameters\n\n### Critical thresholds (act immediately if breached)\n| Parameter | Optimal | Warning | Critical |\n|-----------|---------|---------|----------|\n| Temperature (°C) | 26–30 | 24–25 or 31–33 | <22 or >34 |\n| Dissolved Oxygen (mg/L) | ≥5 | 3–4.9 | <3 |\n| pH | 6.5–8.5 | 6.0–6.4 or 8.6–9.0 | <6 or >9 |\n| Ammonia NH₃ (mg/L) | <0.02 | 0.02–0.1 | >0.1 |\n| Nitrite NO₂ (mg/L) | <0.1 | 0.1–0.5 | >0.5 |\n\n### What to do when parameters are off\n- **Low DO (<3)**: Emergency aeration immediately. Reduce feeding. Check biomass load.\n- **High ammonia (>0.1)**: Partial water change (30–50%). Reduce feeding rate by half. Check pH — ammonia toxicity increases above pH 8.\n- **High nitrite**: Partial water change. Add salt (5–10g/L NaCl temporarily to reduce nitrite uptake).\n- **High temperature (>33°C)**: Shade pond. Add cool water if available.\n- **Low pH (<6.5)**: Lime (agricultural limestone) at 50–100kg/hectare. Check once daily until stable.\n\n## Feeding Guidelines\n\n### Feed types by growth stage\n- **Starter (fry, 0–5g)**: 45–50% protein, feed every 2–3 hours, ~10% body weight/day\n- **Grower (juvenile, 5–50g)**: 40–45% protein, 3–4× daily, 5–7% body weight/day\n- **Finisher (grow-out, 50g+)**: 35–40% protein, 2–3× daily, 3–5% body weight/day\n\n### Signs of overfeeding\n- Uneaten feed on surface 30 min after feeding\n- Ammonia spike next day\n- Cloudy water\n\n### Signs of underfeeding\n- Fish rushing surface aggressively at feeding\n- ABW below target for age\n- Cannibalism in catfish\n\n## Sampling (Weight Checks)\n- Sample every 2 weeks — weigh 30–50 fish per pond\n- Calculate ABW (average body weight) from sample\n- Adjust feed rate to current biomass: `biomass_kg = ABW_g × fish_count / 1000`\n- Daily feed = biomass × feeding_rate%\n\n## Common Diseases\n\n### Bacterial\n- **Motile Aeromonas Septicemia (MAS)**: Red sores, ulcers, hemorrhaging. Treat with oxytetracycline or doxycycline in feed (5–10 days).\n- **Columnaris**: White/grey patches on skin/fins. Improve water quality. Potassium permanganate bath (10 mg/L for 30 min).\n\n### Parasitic\n- **Trichodina / Ichthyo**: White spots, fish flashing. Formalin bath (25 ppm for 1 hour) or salt bath (10g/L for 10–20 min).\n- **Anchor worms / Fish lice**: Visible parasites on skin. Potassium permanganate bath.\n\n### Environmental\n- **Oxygen depletion**: Sudden mass mortality at dawn. Emergency aeration. Reduce biomass.\n- **Ammonia toxicity**: Fish at surface gasping, hemorrhagic gills. Water change + stop feeding.\n\n## Harvest Decision\n- Harvest when ABW reaches target market weight (600g–1kg for catfish)\n- Best practice: partial harvest (remove largest fish first = \"grading harvest\")\n- Avoid feeding 24 hours before harvest\n- Harvest at dawn or dusk (cooler, lower stress)\n- Post-harvest: disinfect pond before restocking (500g lime/m²)\n\n## Economics (typical West Africa)\n- Catfish farm-gate price: 1,500–2,500 XAF/kg (Cameroon); ₦1,200–2,000/kg (Nigeria)\n- Feed cost typically 60–70% of production cost\n- Break-even FCR depends on feed price vs. sale price ratio\n- Target: >30% profit margin on revenue\n\n## Eden AI — Aquaculture Responses\nWhen the farmer's farm is a fish farm (aquaculture):\n- Use \"pond\" not \"pen\" or \"farm unit\"\n- Use \"fingerlings\" not \"chicks\" for young fish\n- Use \"stocking\" not \"placement\"\n- Use \"ABW\" (average body weight) not \"average weight gain\" when discussing growth\n- Reference DO, ammonia, nitrite as the primary health indicators\n- For mortality questions, first ask about water quality — 80% of fish deaths are water quality related\n- Distinguish between catfish (air-breather, more resilient) and tilapia (gill-breather, more sensitive)\n\n## Formulas (use exact arithmetic in answers)\n\n### Average Body Weight (ABW)\n`ABW_g = sum(individual_weights_g) / number_of_fish_weighed`\nSample 5–50 fish, prefer 20–30 for accuracy. Sample bias is the #1 mistake — randomise capture, don't only catch the slow ones near the surface.\n\n### Specific Growth Rate (SGR)\n`SGR (% per day) = ((ln(ABW_now) - ln(ABW_previous)) / days_between) × 100`\n\nWorked example: pond sampled 14 days ago at 120 g, today 180 g.\n`SGR = (ln(180) - ln(120)) / 14 × 100 = (5.193 - 4.787) / 14 × 100 = 2.9 %/day` — healthy grow-out.\n\nHealthy SGR ranges:\n- Catfish 50–500 g: 2.5–4.0 %/day\n- Catfish 500 g+: 1.0–2.0 %/day\n- Tilapia juvenile: 2.0–3.0 %/day\n- Tilapia grow-out: 1.0–2.0 %/day\n\nIf SGR drops below 1 %/day for an active grow-out: check water quality first, then feed quality, then stocking density.\n\n### Biomass\n`biomass_kg = (ABW_g × current_fish_count) / 1000`\n\nWorked example: 1,000 catfish at ABW 250 g → biomass = 250 × 1000 / 1000 = **250 kg**.\n\n### Daily Feed Amount\n`daily_feed_kg = biomass_kg × feeding_rate_percent / 100`\n\nFeeding rate by size:\n- Fry (0–5 g): 8–10%\n- Fingerling (5–50 g): 5–7%\n- Juvenile (50–200 g): 4–5%\n- Grow-out (200–500 g): 3–4%\n- Finisher (500 g+): 2–3%\n\nWorked example: 250 kg biomass at grow-out, 4% rate → 10 kg feed/day, split into 2–3 feedings.\n\n### Feed Conversion Ratio (FCR)\n`FCR = total_feed_consumed_kg / total_weight_gained_kg`\n\nWorked example: pond fed 320 kg over 4 weeks. Started at 200 kg biomass, now 400 kg → gain = 200 kg. `FCR = 320 / 200 = 1.6` — acceptable for catfish.\n\nFCR targets:\n- Catfish: ≤1.5 (excellent), 1.6–1.8 (good), >2.0 (investigate)\n- Tilapia: ≤1.7 (excellent), 1.8–2.0 (good), >2.2 (investigate)\n- Clarias hybrid: ≤1.4\n\nIf FCR is high: feed quality issue, water quality issue (fish under stress eat more for less gain), overfeeding (unused feed rotting), or wrong feeding rate for current ABW.\n\n### Days to Market Estimate\n`days_to_market = ln(target_weight / current_ABW) / SGR × 100`\n\nWorked example: pond at ABW 250 g, target 800 g, current SGR 2.5 %/day.\n`days = ln(800/250) / 2.5 × 100 = ln(3.2) / 2.5 × 100 = 1.163 / 2.5 × 100 = 47 days` (~7 weeks).\n\n## Quick Diagnostics — symptom to likely cause\n\n### Fish at surface gasping for air\n1. Most likely: low dissolved oxygen. Common at dawn after a hot day or after heavy rain (turnover). Aerate immediately.\n2. Possible: ammonia toxicity. Check NH₃ — if >0.1 mg/L, partial water change.\n3. Catfish doing this is less alarming than tilapia (catfish breathe air). But still abnormal — investigate.\n\n### Fish dying overnight, dead fish in morning\n1. Oxygen crash overnight. Common in heavily stocked ponds, after rain, in hot still weather. Check biomass-to-pond-volume ratio.\n2. Predator (snake, otter, bird) — look for puncture wounds or missing fish (not just dead).\n3. Disease outbreak — check for visible lesions, abnormal behaviour pre-death.\n\n### Fish flashing (rubbing against pond bottom/sides)\n- Almost always parasitic — Trichodina, Ichthyophthirius, or fish lice. Salt bath or potassium permanganate.\n\n### White patches on body\n- Columnaris (saddleback disease) or fungal infection (after handling stress). Improve water quality. KMnO₄ bath.\n\n### Red sores, hemorrhagic ulcers\n- Motile Aeromonas Septicemia (MAS). Antibiotic in feed. Quarantine affected fish if possible.\n\n### Fish not eating\n1. Water temperature too low (<22°C) — slows metabolism, normal in cold months. Reduce feeding rate.\n2. Recent ammonia/nitrite spike — fish stressed.\n3. Feed gone bad — check for mould, smell.\n4. Disease early stage — observe for other symptoms.\n\n### Cloudy or green water\n- Green: phytoplankton bloom, generally good (oxygen production) up to a point. Excessive bloom can crash overnight → oxygen crash.\n- Brown/muddy: clay suspension after rain, usually clears in a day. Long-term turbidity → lime to flocculate.\n- Grey/foul-smelling: organic overload from overfeeding. Reduce feed, partial water change.\n\n### Slow growth, low SGR\n1. Water quality (DO, ammonia) — most common.\n2. Wrong feed protein for size — fingerlings need 40-45%, grow-out 35-40%.\n3. Overstocked — biomass too high for pond. Thin out by partial harvest.\n4. Genetics — if you mixed batches, dominant ones eat more. Sort by size.\n\n## Pond Preparation Checklist (new pond / between cycles)\n\n1. **Drain completely** if possible. Sun-dry pond bottom for 5–7 days — kills pathogens and aerates the soil.\n2. **Lime application**: 200–500 kg agricultural lime per hectare. Adjusts pH and kills residual bacteria/parasites.\n3. **Fill with clean water**, let stand 7–10 days for plankton to develop.\n4. **Test water**: pH 6.5–8.5, DO ≥5, ammonia <0.02. If ok, stock.\n5. **Acclimate fingerlings**: float bag in pond water for 20 min before release. Don't dump straight in — temperature shock kills.\n6. **First-week feeding**: light. Fingerlings stressed from transport, full appetite returns by day 3–5.\n\n## Common Beginner Mistakes\n\n- **Overstocking**: more fish per cubic meter than the pond can support. Always calculate biomass capacity first. Catfish in tanks: 50 kg/m³ max for grow-out. Earthen ponds: 4–6 tonnes/hectare.\n- **Underfeeding to save money**: extends grow-out time, hurts FCR, ultimately costs more.\n- **Feeding spoiled feed**: feed loses protein and goes mouldy in humid storage. Use within 30 days of opening, store airtight + dry.\n- **Mixing batches without sorting**: dominant fish bully smaller ones, growth diverges. Sort and segregate every 4 weeks if mixing was unavoidable.\n- **Ignoring water quality until fish die**: by then it's emergency mode. Test DO/pH/ammonia weekly minimum; daily during hot/rainy periods.\n- **No records of feed input**: makes FCR impossible to calculate, makes troubleshooting blind. Log every feeding.\n- **Buying cheap \"no-name\" feed**: protein is often below label. FCR will be terrible. Stick to known brands (Coppens, Skretting, Ranaan, Olam, Aller Aqua) or test small batches.\n- **Mono-sexing tilapia carelessly**: if even 5% female slip in, you'll have hundreds of small unwanted offspring stunting growth in 6 weeks.\n\n## Seasonal & Market Timing (West Africa)\n\n- **Demand spikes**: Christmas/New Year (Dec), Easter (Mar/Apr), Ramadan/Eid (varies), independence days. Plan harvests 2–4 weeks ahead.\n- **Price drops**: post-Christmas glut (Jan), rainy-season abundance (May–Aug in Cameroon/Nigeria) when wild catch is high.\n- **Rainy season risks**: temperature drops, oxygen turnover from stratification breakdown, ammonia after heavy runoff. More frequent water quality checks.\n- **Dry season risks**: high water temperature, evaporation concentrates pollutants. Top-up water and shade where possible.\n- **Hatchery business**: catfish fingerling demand peaks in Feb–April (people stocking ahead of rainy season). Premium prices in this window.\n\n## Stocking Density Rules of Thumb\n\n| System | Catfish | Tilapia |\n|---|---|---|\n| Earthen pond | 1–3 fish/m² | 1–2 fish/m² |\n| Concrete tank | 50–150 fish/m³ | 20–50 fish/m³ |\n| Cage culture | 100–200 fish/m³ | 50–80 fish/m³ |\n| Recirculating (RAS) | 200–400 fish/m³ | 100–150 fish/m³ |\n\nHigher densities require: aeration, frequent water changes, premium feed, vigilant monitoring. Smallholder farmers should stay at the lower end until they have months of clean records.\n\n## Decision: When to Harvest\n\nHarvest when ANY of these is true:\n1. ABW reaches market target (600–1000 g catfish, 400–800 g tilapia).\n2. SGR has dropped below 1 %/day for 2+ consecutive samples — feed conversion is now poor, more days = more cost without proportional gain.\n3. Pond is approaching biomass capacity — overcrowding suppresses growth and risks oxygen crash.\n4. Feed prices spiked or sale prices peaked — economic harvest decision.\n5. Disease outbreak — partial emergency harvest of healthy stock to limit losses.\n\nDo NOT harvest when:\n- Fish under treatment (antibiotic withdrawal period — typically 14–21 days).\n- Within 24h of feeding (fish are gut-full, weight is misleading and storage degrades).\n- During heavy rain (stress, transport difficulty).\n\n";
export const POULTRY_KNOWLEDGE: string = "# Poultry Knowledge Base — West African Poultry Farming\n\n## Species Overview\n\n### Broilers (meat chickens)\n- Most common: Cobb 500, Ross 308, Hubbard\n- Cycle: 6–8 weeks from day-old chick to slaughter\n- Market weight: 2.0–2.8 kg live weight\n- Feed bands: Starter (1–14 days, 22–24% protein), Grower (15–28 days, 20–22%), Finisher (29 days+, 18–20%)\n- FCR target: 1.6–1.8 (excellent), 1.9–2.1 (acceptable), >2.2 (investigate)\n- Stocking density: 10–12 birds/m² (deep-litter floor); 20–25 birds/m² (cage)\n- Mortality target: <5% over the cycle. >8% = systemic problem.\n\n### Layers (egg-producing chickens)\n- Most common in West Africa: ISA Brown, Lohmann Brown, Hy-Line Brown, NERA black\n- Lifecycle phases: Chick (1–5 weeks) → Grower (6–12 weeks) → Pullet (13–17 weeks) → Pre-lay (18–20 weeks) → Laying (21+ weeks, peaks at 28–35 weeks, productive through 72+)\n- Feed bands: Starter (1–6 weeks, 20–22% protein), Grower (7–14 weeks, 16–18%), Developer/Pullet (15–18 weeks, 14–16%), Pre-lay (18–20 weeks, 16–17% + calcium build), Layer mash (21+ weeks, 16–18% + 3.5–4.0% calcium)\n- Production peak: 90–95% lay rate (28–35 weeks), drops gradually to 65–75% by 70+ weeks\n- Cull or restart: when lay rate drops below 60% and feed cost per egg exceeds market price\n\n### Dual-purpose / native breeds\n- Kuroiler, Sasso, Noiler, Funaab Alpha — popular in West Africa for backyard farms\n- Slower growth than commercial broilers (~16 weeks to market) but hardier and dual-purpose\n- Lower input costs, lower output, better margins for smallholder farms\n\n## Critical Parameters\n\n### Temperature (brooding stage — first 2–3 weeks is everything)\n| Age | Optimal °C |\n|-----|------------|\n| Day 1–3 | 32–35 |\n| Day 4–7 | 30–32 |\n| Week 2 | 27–29 |\n| Week 3 | 24–26 |\n| Week 4+ | 18–24 |\n\n**Critical**: chicks under 24°C in week 1 will huddle, get crushed, develop respiratory issues. Use heat lamps, kerosene heaters, or charcoal pots with proper ventilation.\n\n### Ventilation\n- Adult birds need ~5 m³/hour of fresh air per bird\n- Smell of ammonia in the coop = bedding too wet, ventilation too low — change litter, increase airflow\n- Too much ventilation in brooding kills chicks via cold stress\n\n### Lighting (layers)\n- Pullets (1–18 weeks): natural daylight only — extending light early triggers premature lay (smaller eggs, shorter productive cycle)\n- Pre-lay onwards: 14–16 hours/day light. Add artificial light (LED 60–100 lux) if natural daylight is shorter.\n- Sudden light changes cause stress and drops in lay rate. Adjust by 15 min/day max.\n\n## Feeding Guidelines\n\n### Daily feed by age (broiler)\n| Week | Feed/bird/day (g) |\n|------|-------------------|\n| 1 | 25–30 |\n| 2 | 60–70 |\n| 3 | 100–110 |\n| 4 | 130–145 |\n| 5 | 165–180 |\n| 6 | 195–210 |\n| 7 | 220–235 |\n| 8 | 230+ |\n\n### Daily feed by age (layer in production)\n- Pullet phase: ~70–90 g/bird/day\n- Pre-lay: ~100–110 g/bird/day\n- Peak lay (28–35 wk): ~115–125 g/bird/day\n- Late lay (60+ wk): ~110 g/bird/day (drop slightly to control body weight)\n\n### Signs of overfeeding\n- Wet droppings, ammonia smell builds fast\n- FCR climbs past 1.9 (broilers) or 2.4 (layers)\n- Birds becoming sluggish; legs splay (broilers)\n\n### Signs of underfeeding\n- Birds crowd feeders aggressively at feeding time\n- Body weight below standard for age\n- Layers: drop in lay rate within 7 days\n\n## Common Diseases\n\n### Viral\n- **Newcastle Disease (NCD)**: paralysis, twisted necks, sudden mortality. NO TREATMENT. Vaccinate at day 7, day 21, week 8, then every 3 months.\n- **Infectious Bronchitis (IB)**: respiratory distress, drop in lay, soft-shelled eggs. Vaccinate alongside NCD.\n- **Gumboro (IBD)**: bloody diarrhea, prostration, mortality 2–4 weeks. Vaccinate day 14 and day 21.\n- **Avian Influenza (HPAI)**: notifiable; if suspected, contact veterinary authorities immediately. No treatment, mass cull required.\n\n### Bacterial\n- **Coccidiosis**: bloody droppings, hunched posture. Treat with amprolium or sulfadimidine 5–7 days. Coccidiostat in feed prevents recurrence.\n- **Fowl typhoid (Salmonella gallinarum)**: green diarrhea, sudden mortality. Antibiotics (enrofloxacin) + improved hygiene.\n- **CRD/Mycoplasma**: rattling breath, swollen sinuses. Tylosin or tilmicosin in water, 5 days.\n- **E. coli**: airsacculitis, mortality after stress events. Antibiotics + reduce stress factors.\n\n### Parasitic\n- **Lice/mites**: feather damage, scratching, drop in lay. Pyrethroid spray on birds and coop.\n- **Worms (roundworm, tapeworm)**: weight loss, pale combs. Deworm with albendazole or piperazine every 8 weeks.\n\n## Vaccination Schedule (typical layer)\n\n| Age | Vaccine | Method |\n|-----|---------|--------|\n| Day 1 | Marek's | Hatchery (subcutaneous) |\n| Day 7 | NCD + IB | Eye drop or drinking water |\n| Day 14 | Gumboro (IBD) | Drinking water |\n| Day 21 | NCD + IB booster | Drinking water |\n| Day 28 | Gumboro booster | Drinking water |\n| Week 6 | Fowl Pox | Wing-web stab |\n| Week 8 | NCD (lasota) | Drinking water |\n| Week 10 | Deworming | Oral |\n| Week 16 | NCD + IB + EDS | Injection (final pre-lay) |\n| Every 3 mo | NCD booster | Water |\n\n## Formulas (use exact arithmetic)\n\n### Mortality rate\n`Mortality % = (deaths / initial flock size) × 100`\n\nWorked example: started with 500 chicks, lost 18 by week 8.\n`Mortality = 18 / 500 × 100 = 3.6%` — within target (<5%).\n\n### Survival rate\n`Survival % = (current count / initial count) × 100`\n\n### Daily gain (broilers)\n`Daily gain (g) = (current weight - previous weight) / days between checks`\n\nWorked example: week 4 weight 1.0 kg, week 5 weight 1.5 kg.\n`Daily gain = (1500 - 1000) / 7 = 71 g/day` — on target for Cobb 500.\n\n### Feed Conversion Ratio (FCR — broilers)\n`FCR = total feed consumed (kg) / total live weight produced (kg)`\n\nWorked example: 500 birds, 1,200 kg feed used, average 2.0 kg per bird at slaughter.\n`Total weight = 500 × 2.0 = 1000 kg`\n`FCR = 1200 / 1000 = 1.2` — excellent (suspicious if too low; typical good is 1.6–1.8).\n\n### Feed Conversion Ratio (layers — kg feed per dozen eggs)\n`FCR layer = total feed (kg) / (total eggs / 12)`\n\nWorked example: 100 layers eat 12 kg/day, lay 80 eggs/day.\n`Daily FCR = 12 / (80/12) = 12 / 6.67 = 1.8 kg feed per dozen eggs` — acceptable (good: 1.5–1.7).\n\n### Production rate (lay rate)\n`Lay rate % = (eggs collected / hens housed) × 100`\n\nWorked example: 400 hens, 360 eggs today.\n`Lay rate = 360 / 400 × 100 = 90%` — peak production.\n\n### Cost per egg\n`Cost per egg = total expenses (feed + chicks + meds + labor + power) / total eggs`\n\nUse rolling 30 days for stable numbers.\n\n### Cost per bird (broilers)\n`Cost per bird = total cycle expenses / birds reaching market`\n\nIf cycle cost is 950,000 XAF and 480 birds reach market, cost per bird is 1,979 XAF. If sale price is 2,500 XAF/bird, profit margin is ~21%.\n\n### Days to market (broilers)\n`Days remaining = (target weight - current weight) / current daily gain`\n\nWorked example: bird at 1.4 kg, gaining 70 g/day, target 2.2 kg.\n`Days = (2200 - 1400) / 70 = 11.4 days`\n\n## Quick Diagnostics — symptom to likely cause\n\n### Sudden mass mortality\n1. Disease outbreak (NCD or HPAI most likely if rapid). Check for nervous symptoms.\n2. Heat stress (hot afternoon, no airflow). Birds gasping, wings spread.\n3. Water cut off. Check water lines.\n4. Predation (snake, fox in the coop overnight).\n5. Suffocation (overcrowding at corners during cold night).\n\n### Birds gasping with open beaks\n1. Heat stress (most likely if ambient >32°C). Add fans, mist, cool water.\n2. Respiratory disease (CRD, IB). Listen for rattling breath.\n3. Ammonia poisoning (high ammonia from wet litter). Change bedding immediately.\n\n### Drop in lay rate (layers)\n1. Stress event (predator scare, sudden noise, vaccination). Recovers in 3–7 days.\n2. Disease — IB, EDS, fatty liver. Check egg quality (soft shells, watery whites).\n3. Light schedule changed. Verify 14–16 hr/day.\n4. Feed switched or feed quality drop. Test protein.\n5. Bird age — gradual decline after week 50 is normal.\n6. Heat stress.\n\n### Bloody droppings\n- Coccidiosis (most likely in 2–6 week chicks). Treat amprolium 5 days.\n- Necrotic enteritis (less common, often follows coccidiosis). Antibiotic.\n- Internal parasites. Deworm.\n\n### Pale combs and wattles\n- Anemia (parasites, blood loss).\n- Internal worms.\n- Vitamin deficiency.\n\n### Birds piling/huddling\n- Cold stress (most likely brooding age). Increase heat.\n- Fear (predator/loud noise outside).\n\n### Cannibalism / pecking\n- Overcrowding — reduce density.\n- Lighting too bright. Use red bulbs or dim.\n- Protein deficiency or salt deficiency. Test feed.\n- Boredom — add scratch litter, hanging cabbage.\n\n### Cracked or thin-shelled eggs\n- Calcium deficiency. Increase oyster shell or limestone in feed.\n- Old hens. Cull bottom 20% if persistent.\n- Heat stress (afternoon). Cool the coop.\n- IB or EDS virus. Vaccinate next batch.\n\n## Brooding Setup Checklist (first 2 weeks decide the cycle)\n\n1. **Pre-warm the brooder 24h before chicks arrive** — temperature stable at 32–35°C.\n2. **Litter**: 5–10cm deep wood shavings or rice husks. Dry, clean.\n3. **Heat source**: 1 brooder lamp (250W) per 100 chicks. Backup gas/charcoal in case of power cut.\n4. **Water**: 2 drinkers per 100 chicks, sugar water (5g/L) for first 2 hours to combat transport stress.\n5. **Feed**: chick starter mash spread on paper sheets for first 3 days (chicks find it easier).\n6. **Light**: 24 hours for first 3 days, then 23 hours from day 4–7, then natural light.\n7. **Density**: 30 chicks/m² for week 1, reduce as they grow.\n8. **Daily checks**: count droppings, listen for chirping (loud chirps = cold; silent = ok or sick), watch huddle pattern.\n\n## Common Beginner Mistakes\n\n- **Cheap fake feed**: bags labeled \"20% protein\" are often 14–16% in unbranded markets. FCR will be terrible. Stick to known brands (Hybrid, ECWA, Top Feeds, Vital, Olam).\n- **Skipping vaccinations**: NCD will wipe out a flock in 72 hours. The vaccine costs less than 50 XAF per bird.\n- **Mixed-age flocks in same coop**: disease spreads from older to younger. Always all-in / all-out per coop.\n- **Buying chicks from unverified hatcheries**: poor genetics, parent stock disease. Pay more for grade-A hatcheries.\n- **Watering down feed costs at expense of protein**: never substitute >20% of complete feed with maize/cassava — protein drops, FCR doubles.\n- **Late vaccination scheduling**: missing day-7 NCD because \"the chicks look fine\" — by the time they look unwell, it's too late.\n- **Litter not turned**: caked litter = ammonia release = respiratory issues. Turn or top up weekly.\n- **Predator gaps**: snakes, rats, civets enter through one missed gap. Inspect coop perimeter weekly.\n- **Layers in dim light too long**: pullets force-lit too early lay smaller eggs and burn out by week 50.\n- **Selling broilers too early or too late**: each extra day past 6 weeks costs more than the weight gained. Track FCR daily; sell when FCR climbs above 2.0.\n\n## Seasonal & Market Timing (West Africa)\n\n- **Demand peaks**: Christmas/New Year, Easter, Eid, independence days, end-of-month for layers (institutional egg buyers). Plan broiler harvests 6 weeks ahead.\n- **Price drops**: post-festive glut (Jan, post-Eid), rainy season market closures.\n- **Rainy season risks**: cold-stress on chicks, mud increases coccidiosis. Raise the brooder, dry litter daily.\n- **Dry/harmattan season risks**: respiratory disease (dust + dryness), water shortage. Check water cleanliness daily.\n- **Chick supply**: prices spike in Nov (everyone gearing up for Christmas). Order 2 months ahead for Christmas-target broilers.\n\n## Stocking Density Rules\n\n| System | Broilers | Layers |\n|---|---|---|\n| Deep litter | 10–12 birds/m² | 6–8 birds/m² |\n| Slatted floor | 14–16 birds/m² | 10–12 birds/m² |\n| Battery cage | 22–25 birds/m² (mostly illegal in EU; common in WA) | 14–16 birds/m² |\n| Free range | 1–2 birds/m² | 0.5–1 bird/m² |\n\nHigher density requires: better ventilation, more drinker/feeder line, more frequent litter management.\n\n## Decision: When to Sell Broilers\n\nSell when ANY of these:\n1. Average weight reaches market target (2.0–2.5 kg).\n2. FCR climbs above 2.0 — feed converting poorly, more days = more cost without gain.\n3. Mortality spike (>1% in 48 hours) — cut losses, sell healthy stock.\n4. Feed price spiked or sale price peaked.\n5. Disease outbreak — partial emergency harvest of unaffected birds.\n\nDo NOT sell when:\n- Within antibiotic withdrawal period (typically 5–14 days, check label).\n- During heavy rain/cold (transport stress, lower buyer confidence).\n- 24h after feeding (gut-full birds weigh more but stress drops live weight before sale).\n\n## Decision: When to Cull Layers\n\nCull when ANY of these:\n1. Lay rate drops below 60% and stays there for 4 weeks.\n2. Bird age >75 weeks AND egg shell quality dropping (cracked, soft).\n3. Feed cost per egg approaches or exceeds market price.\n4. Disease outbreak with permanent damage (chronic CRD).\n\nBest practice: cull bottom 20% of producers monthly (skinny birds, dirty vents, no recent lay) — they eat feed without producing.\n\n## Eden AI — Poultry Responses\nWhen the farmer's farm is poultry:\n- Use \"flock\", \"birds\", \"hens\", \"chicks\", \"broilers\", \"layers\" appropriately.\n- Reference NCD/IB/Gumboro vaccination by name when relevant.\n- For mortality questions, ask first about: temperature in past 24h, vaccination status, water cleanliness, litter condition.\n- Distinguish broilers (FCR-focused, short cycle) from layers (lay rate-focused, long cycle).\n- Use kg for broiler weights and dozen eggs for layer production.\n";
export const RABBIT_KNOWLEDGE: string = "# Rabbits Knowledge Base — Smallholder Rabbit Farming\n\n## Species Overview\n\n### Meat rabbits (most common)\n- Breeds: New Zealand White, Californian, Flemish Giant, Chinchilla, local crosses\n- Cycle: ~12–14 weeks from kit (newborn) to market\n- Market weight: 2.0–2.5 kg live weight (1.2–1.5 kg dressed)\n- FCR target: 3.0–3.5 (good), 4.0+ (investigate). Higher than poultry but rabbits convert forage.\n- Breeding age: does ready at 5–6 months (4–4.5 kg), bucks at 6–7 months\n- Litter size: 6–10 kits per kindling; 8 average\n- Litters per doe per year: 5–7 (with 4-week kit-to-rebreed cycle), realistic smallholder = 4–5\n- Mortality target: <10% kit-to-weaning, <5% post-weaning\n\n### Breeder rabbits (does and bucks)\n- A productive doe yields 30–50 weaned kits per year\n- Buck:doe ratio 1:8 to 1:10 (one buck services 8–10 does)\n- Bucks productive 3–4 years; does 2.5–3 years before fertility drops\n- Cull does that miss 3 consecutive matings, deliver <5 kits per litter twice in a row, or show recurring infections.\n\n## Lifecycle Phases (meat rabbits)\n\n| Phase | Age | What's happening |\n|-------|-----|------------------|\n| Kit | Week 1–4 | Nest box, on doe's milk. Eyes open day 10. |\n| Weanling | Week 5–8 | Just weaned; vulnerable to digestive upset. Pellet + hay. |\n| Grower | Week 9–14 | Fastest growth phase. Highest feed intake. |\n| Market-ready | Week 15+ | 2.0–2.5 kg, ready for slaughter. Past this, FCR worsens. |\n\n## Hutch Setup\n\n### Critical parameters\n| Parameter | Optimal | Acceptable | Action if outside |\n|-----------|---------|------------|-------------------|\n| Temperature (°C) | 15–22 | 10–28 | >30°C: heat stress (give frozen bottles); <10°C: insulate, reduce ventilation |\n| Humidity | 50–70% | 40–80% | High humidity + heat = respiratory disease risk |\n| Floor type | Wire mesh (15×15mm) over solid base | Bamboo slats | Wood-only floors cause sore hocks |\n| Hutch size | 0.5 m² for grower, 1 m² for doe + litter | — | Overcrowding causes fighting and disease |\n| Ventilation | Good airflow, no direct draft | — | Smell of ammonia = ventilation too low |\n\n### Stocking density\n| Type | Per hutch |\n|------|-----------|\n| Single doe + litter (kits up to 4 weeks) | 1 m² |\n| Doe alone | 0.5–0.7 m² |\n| Buck | 0.5 m² (always solo — bucks fight) |\n| Growers (8+ weeks) | 0.15 m² per rabbit, max 6–8 per group hutch |\n| Weanlings (5–7 weeks) | 0.1 m² per rabbit |\n\nNEVER mix mature bucks together (they will fight, often fatally). Adult does can sometimes be group-housed but will fight if a doe in heat is near a buck.\n\n## Feeding Guidelines\n\n### Daily intake by stage\n| Stage | Pellets (g/day) | Hay | Greens |\n|-------|-----------------|-----|--------|\n| Kit (suckling) | — | — | — (on milk) |\n| Weanling (week 5–8) | 60–80 | unlimited | introduce slowly, small amounts |\n| Grower (week 9–14) | 120–150 | unlimited | 200–300 g greens/day |\n| Adult doe (not pregnant) | 100–120 | unlimited | 200 g greens |\n| Pregnant doe | 150–180 | unlimited | 250–300 g greens |\n| Lactating doe + litter | 200–280 | unlimited | 300–400 g greens |\n| Buck | 100–120 | unlimited | 200 g |\n\n### Feed types\n- **Commercial pellets**: 16–18% protein, contains all minerals. Use for grower phase (fastest growth).\n- **Hay**: Critical for digestion. Provides fiber that prevents GI stasis. Lucerne (alfalfa), grass hay, dried groundnut hay.\n- **Greens**: cabbage, kale, carrot tops, spinach, lettuce (small), banana leaves, sweet-potato vines, moringa. Introduce ONE new green at a time over a week.\n- **Concentrate (DIY)**: maize, wheat bran, groundnut cake, soybean cake, fish meal, salt, bone meal. Cheaper but inconsistent.\n\n### Forbidden / dangerous foods\n- Iceberg lettuce in large amounts (causes diarrhea)\n- Onions, garlic, leeks (toxic)\n- Avocado, rhubarb, raw beans (toxic)\n- Wet/wilted greens (cause bloat)\n- Bread, cookies, sweets (cause cecal dysbiosis)\n- Cabbage in large amounts (gas; small portions ok)\n\n### Signs of overfeeding pellets\n- Soft droppings, wet vent area\n- Refusing hay (only eats pellets — bad sign)\n- Obesity (back not visible, fat rolls)\n- Gut stasis when feed switches\n\n### Signs of underfeeding\n- Slow growth (weight below 1.5 kg at week 12)\n- Aggressive feeder behavior\n- Doe eating own kits (severe protein/calcium deficiency)\n\n## Common Diseases\n\n### Bacterial\n- **Pasteurellosis (snuffles)**: most common. Sneezing, white nasal discharge, eye infection. Spreads via contact and aerosol. Treat: enrofloxacin 5–7 days. Cull chronic carriers (shed bacteria for life).\n- **Coccidiosis (intestinal)**: bloody/mucousy diarrhea in 4–10 week kits. Treat: sulfaquinoxaline or amprolium 5–7 days. Prevent: clean water, dry hutches, coccidiostat in feed for high-risk farms.\n- **Coccidiosis (hepatic / liver form)**: weight loss, pot belly. Confirmed at slaughter (white spots on liver). Same treatment.\n- **Enterotoxemia**: sudden death in weanlings, often after antibiotic use or sudden feed change. Treat: probiotics + electrolytes; usually fatal.\n\n### Parasitic\n- **Ear mites (Psoroptes cuniculi)**: scratching ears, brown crust inside ear. Treat: ivermectin injection or topical mineral oil.\n- **Fur mites (Cheyletiella)**: dandruff-like flakes on back. Ivermectin.\n- **Internal worms**: weight loss, dull coat. Deworm every 2–3 months with ivermectin or fenbendazole.\n\n### Environmental\n- **Sore hocks (pododermatitis)**: ulcers on bottom of feet. Caused by wire-only floors or wet/dirty bedding. Treat: provide solid resting board (15cm × 25cm wood) in each hutch.\n- **Heat stroke**: rabbits don't sweat. >32°C is dangerous. Ears bright red, panting, lying flat. Treat: cool water on ears, frozen bottles, shade, fan.\n- **Trichobezoars (hairballs)**: blockage from grooming. Prevent with hay (high fiber). Treat: pineapple juice, simethicone.\n\n### Reproductive\n- **Stuck kindling (dystocia)**: doe straining without delivering. Massage abdomen, oxytocin if available. Often fatal.\n- **Mastitis**: hard hot mammary gland, doe rejects kits. Antibiotics. Foster kits to another doe if possible.\n- **Cannibalism of kits**: stress, first-time doe, low protein. Improve feed, reduce disturbance.\n\n## Vaccination\n\nRabbits in West Africa typically need:\n- **RHD (Rabbit Hemorrhagic Disease) vaccine**: at 8 weeks, then every 6 months. Mandatory in regions with outbreaks.\n- **Myxomatosis**: less common in WA but vaccinate if local outbreaks reported.\n\nMost smallholder farms do NOT vaccinate routinely (cost vs. risk). If buying expensive breeding stock, vaccinate.\n\n## Breeding & Kindling\n\n### Breeding management\n- Always bring the doe to the buck's hutch (does are territorial; buck performs poorly in unfamiliar hutch).\n- Successful mating: buck mounts, falls off backwards or sideways. Repeat after 5 minutes for higher conception.\n- Pregnancy test: palpate abdomen at day 10–12 (small grape-sized lumps).\n- Gestation: 30–32 days.\n\n### Kindling preparation\n- Day 28: place a clean nest box in doe's hutch with shredded paper or hay.\n- Doe pulls fur from her belly to line nest 24–48h before kindling.\n- Most kindlings happen at night/early morning. Check first thing in the morning.\n- Newborn kits: tiny, hairless, eyes closed. Doe nurses 1–2 times per day for 5 minutes only — DO NOT think she's neglecting them.\n\n### Re-breeding schedule (intensive)\n- Re-breed doe at week 3–4 after kindling (kits still nursing).\n- Wean kits at week 4–5; doe rests 2–7 days then kindle again.\n- Yields ~6–7 litters/year. Hard on does — culling required by year 3.\n\n### Re-breeding schedule (semi-intensive, recommended for smallholder)\n- Re-breed doe at week 6–8 after kindling.\n- Wean at week 5–6.\n- Yields ~4–5 litters/year. Healthier does, longer productive life.\n\n## Formulas (use exact arithmetic)\n\n### Kit survival rate\n`Survival % = (kits weaned / kits born alive) × 100`\n\nWorked example: doe kindles 9 kits, 7 survive to wean.\n`Survival = 7 / 9 × 100 = 78%` — average. Below 70% = problem (cold, disease, low milk).\n\n### Doe productivity\n`Annual kits per doe = litters/year × kits per litter × survival rate`\n\nWorked example: 5 litters, 8 kits/litter, 80% survival.\n`Annual = 5 × 8 × 0.8 = 32 kits/doe/year`\n\n### Feed Conversion Ratio (rabbits)\n`FCR = total feed (kg) / total live weight gain (kg)`\n\nWorked example: 50 grower rabbits, 240 kg pellets used over 8 weeks, average gain 1.6 kg/rabbit.\n`Total gain = 50 × 1.6 = 80 kg`\n`FCR = 240 / 80 = 3.0` — good.\n\n### Cost per market rabbit\n`Cost per rabbit = (cycle feed + chicks/kits + meds + share of doe maintenance) / market rabbits sold`\n\nDoe maintenance is real: a doe eats year-round whether or not she's producing. Allocate her annual feed cost across the kits she produces.\n\n### Days to market\n`Days remaining = (target weight - current weight) / current daily gain`\n\nWorked example: 1.4 kg rabbit gaining 30 g/day, target 2.2 kg.\n`Days = (2200 - 1400) / 30 = 27 days` — ~4 weeks.\n\n## Quick Diagnostics — symptom to likely cause\n\n### Sudden death\n- Heat stroke (most likely if hot weather + poor ventilation).\n- Enterotoxemia (digestive crash, often after feed change).\n- Predation (snake, dog, mongoose; check for wounds).\n- RHD outbreak (multiple deaths same day).\n\n### White nasal discharge, sneezing\n- Pasteurellosis (snuffles). Isolate, treat with enrofloxacin. Highly contagious.\n\n### Bloody/mucousy diarrhea (kits, week 4–10)\n- Coccidiosis. Treat amprolium or sulfa.\n- Bacterial enteritis. Antibiotic + electrolytes.\n\n### Soft / wet droppings\n- Too much pellets, not enough hay.\n- Sudden feed change.\n- Dehydration → re-fed too much pellet.\n\n### Doe rejects kits / cannibalism\n- First-time mother (often improves second litter).\n- Stress (loud noise, predator scare, frequent inspection).\n- Low protein/calcium in feed.\n- Mastitis.\n\n### Limping, swollen feet\n- Sore hocks. Add solid resting board, dry the hutch.\n- Hutch wire mesh too sharp or wrong gauge.\n\n### Slow growth (below 1.5 kg at week 12)\n1. Internal parasites — deworm.\n2. Coccidiosis (subclinical) — check droppings, treat.\n3. Feed protein too low.\n4. Overcrowding stress.\n5. Genetics (low-quality breeding stock).\n\n### Hair loss / dandruff\n- Fur mites. Ivermectin.\n- Ringworm (less common). Antifungal cream.\n- Stress / fighting (group housing too dense).\n\n### Doe not breeding\n- Out of season (does have receptive cycles; if rejects buck 3 times, wait a week).\n- Buck infertile (test with another doe).\n- Obesity (overfed doe; reduce feed, lose weight, retry).\n- Disease (Pasteurella often sterilizes).\n\n## Common Beginner Mistakes\n\n- **Buying cheap unverified breeding stock**: poor genetics + Pasteurella carriers = chronic snuffles forever. Pay for grade-A bucks and does from established farms.\n- **Wire-only flooring**: causes sore hocks within weeks. Always provide a solid resting area.\n- **Mixing breeders**: bucks fight (sometimes fatal). Always solo-house bucks.\n- **Sudden feed changes**: kills weanlings via enterotoxemia. Transition new feed over 7 days.\n- **Skipping hay**: pellets-only causes GI stasis. Hay is non-negotiable.\n- **Overfeeding pellets to does**: obese does don't conceive. Restrict feed when not pregnant/nursing.\n- **Re-breeding too aggressively**: 6+ litters/year burns out does in 18 months.\n- **Ignoring snuffles in one rabbit**: it's contagious. Quarantine immediately or you'll lose the herd.\n- **Mass weaning (taking all kits at once)**: doe gets mastitis from sudden milk buildup. Wean gradually over 3 days.\n- **Hutches too small**: rabbits get aggressive, fight, develop sores. Calculate space before stocking.\n\n## Seasonal & Market Timing (West Africa)\n\n- **Dry/harmattan season**: respiratory disease risk increases (dust + dryness aggravate snuffles). Provide humidifier or wet sacks.\n- **Rainy season**: hutches stay wet, coccidiosis spikes, sore hocks worsen. Raise hutches, add drainage.\n- **Demand peaks**: Christmas, New Year, Easter, Eid. Plan grower batches 12 weeks ahead.\n- **Lean periods**: post-festive (Jan–Feb). Consider holding stock or processing into smoked rabbit (better margin).\n- **Market acceptance**: rabbit meat is a niche in WA but growing. Premium customers (hotels, restaurants, urban middle class) pay 1.5–2× chicken price per kg dressed.\n\n## Decision: When to Sell Growers\n\nSell when ANY of these:\n1. Average weight reaches 2.0–2.5 kg (week 12–14 typically).\n2. FCR climbs above 3.5 — feed converting poorly.\n3. Hutch overcrowding — split or sell early.\n4. Disease outbreak — emergency sell unaffected stock.\n5. Festive demand window — sell at peak price even if a week early.\n\nDo NOT sell when:\n- Antibiotic withdrawal period (typically 14 days).\n- Within 24h of feeding (gut-full = misleading weight).\n- Excessive heat (transport stress kills 1–3% en route).\n\n## Decision: When to Cull a Doe\n\nCull when ANY of these:\n1. Misses 3 consecutive successful matings.\n2. Litter size drops below 5 for 2 consecutive litters.\n3. Kit survival to wean drops below 60% for 2 litters.\n4. Chronic snuffles (Pasteurella carrier) — biosecurity risk.\n5. Age >3 years AND productivity declining.\n6. Mastitis recurring more than once.\n\nCull bucks when:\n1. Refuses to breed for 4+ weeks.\n2. Daughters' litter sizes consistently below average (genetic issue).\n3. Age >4 years.\n\n## Eden AI — Rabbit Responses\nWhen the farmer's farm is rabbits:\n- Use \"rabbits\", \"kits\", \"doe\", \"buck\", \"weanling\", \"grower\", \"litter\".\n- Use \"hutch\" not \"coop\" or \"pen\".\n- Reference Pasteurella, coccidiosis, sore hocks, GI stasis as the recurring health issues.\n- For mortality questions, ask first about: temperature, hutch hygiene, feed change history, hay availability.\n- Distinguish kit-stage (week 1–4, on milk) from weanling (week 5–8, vulnerable) from grower (week 9+).\n- Use kg for weights, weeks for age, litters for breeding output.\n";
